~ test_protected_policy.he — confirms protected.he is valid, ordinary HE
   and that its objects can be read via flat summon, matching the tag
   names used by #protected[N]. Stage A / step 1 of the protection roadmap.

   Scope: format + readability only. No enforcement reads this file yet. ~

summon "protected.he"

~ Bare #protected ~
if protected.mode is "cached" then [
  say "Base tier: cached mode confirmed"
]
say "Base tier endpoint: " + protected.endpoint

~ #protected1 ~
if protected1.mode is "cached" then [
  say "Plan A: cached mode confirmed"
]
say "Plan A grace period: " + protected1.graceSeconds + " seconds"

~ #protected2 ~
if protected2.mode is "live" then [
  say "Plan B: live mode confirmed (no offline grace, by design)"
]
say "Plan B endpoint: " + protected2.endpoint

~ Confirm tag-name symmetry: the object name in protected.he matches
   the tag name used in #protected[N] exactly, so a future enforcement
   step can look up policy by tag name with no translation. ~
say "Policy object names match tag names: protected, protected1, protected2"

say "All protected.he policy tests passed!"
